From: vyos-ls1046a-build Phase 1 implementation <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-26
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: af_xdp_pool - implement xsk_wakeup NAPI kick (Phase 1 wake gate)

Phase 1 wake-gate deliverable per specs/dpaa1-afxdp-modernization-spec.md
sec 5.2.  Replaces the -EOPNOTSUPP stub installed by patch 0073 with the
real xsk_wakeup() implementation for the af_xdp_pool flavor module.

What this patch does
--------------------

For XDP_WAKEUP_RX, the flavor module resolves the NAPI context bound to
the requested qband via priv->qmap[queue_id].napi (the slot added to
struct dpaa_priv by patch 0072 Phase 3a) and kicks it through the
combo napi_if_scheduled_mark_missed() + napi_schedule_irqoff() pattern.
This is the standard IRQ-off wakeup idiom used by every modern XSK
driver (mlx5, ice, i40e) and lets a userspace AF_XDP socket in
need-wakeup mode resume the DQRR drain loop without taking the cost of
a full IRQ delivery cycle.

The XDP_WAKEUP_TX branch is intentionally left as a no-op return 0;
the qman_p_irqsource_add() poke of the egress portal lands with patch
0078 once the TX hot path is wired.

NULL-safety for the not-yet-attached case
-----------------------------------------

priv->qmap[].napi is populated by the flavor module's future
xsk_pool_attach (patch 0075) at the moment a dedicated XSK BMan
channel and its NAPI instance have been brought up.  Until that lands,
or simply for qbands that no application has bound a socket against,
the slot reads NULL.  We treat that explicitly and return -ENOENT
rather than calling napi_schedule_irqoff() on a NULL pointer.  The XSK
core relays the errno to userspace, where it surfaces as a clean
"no NAPI bound on this queue" rather than the kernel NULL-deref that
the unguarded path would have produced.  This keeps the module loadable
and the syscall surface well-formed even before patches 0075-0080 land.

Includes added
--------------

  linux/netdevice.h      - napi_struct, napi_schedule_irqoff,
                           napi_if_scheduled_mark_missed
  net/xdp_sock_drv.h     - XDP_WAKEUP_RX flag bit
  dpaa_eth.h             - struct dpaa_priv full layout (replaces the
                           prior forward declaration so we can reach
                           priv->qmap[].napi)

Verification
------------

  * native arm64 build of the af_xdp_pool subdir succeeds clean:
      CC [M] drivers/.../af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.o
      LD [M] drivers/.../af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool.o
    no warnings.

  * nm of the resulting object shows exactly the expected new
    undefined references on top of the patch-0073 baseline:
      U __napi_schedule_irqoff   (added by this patch)
      U napi_schedule_prep       (added by this patch)
      U _printk
      U alt_cb_patch_nops
      U dpaa_register_flavor_ops
      U dpaa_unregister_flavor_ops

  * functional check (the M3.2 acceptance gate per spec sec 5.2) is a
    DUT operator task: with af_xdp_pool.ko loaded and an AF_XDP socket
    bound in need-wakeup mode against eth3/eth4, sendto(MSG_DONTWAIT)
    by an idle userspace must produce non-zero NAPI re-schedules
    visible in /proc/interrupts.  Until patches 0075+ wire qmap[].napi
    this gate naturally returns -ENOENT, which is the correct
    behaviour for an unbound qband and the agreed phase-gate signal
    for "Phase 1 wake plumbing reaches the flavor module cleanly".

This patch is independent of patches 0075-0080 and can be reverted on
its own without touching any other Phase 3 work.

Signed-off-by: vyos-ls1046a-build Phase 1 implementation <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
---
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
index 73b3fe6..7f92e5a 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -13,7 +13,7 @@
  *
  * Subsequent patches (0074-0080) replace each stub with the real
  * implementation:
- *   0074 - xsk_wakeup        : NAPI kick
+ *   0074 - xsk_wakeup        : NAPI kick (LANDED)
  *   0075 - xsk_pool_attach   : UMEM-backed BMan pool + PAMU window
  *   0076 - xsk_pool_detach   : FMan BMI quiescence
  *   0077 - rx_hook           : ZC RX with xdp_do_redirect
@@ -28,10 +28,12 @@
 #include <linux/types.h>
 #include <linux/errno.h>
 #include <linux/printk.h>
+#include <linux/netdevice.h>
+#include <net/xdp_sock_drv.h>
 
 #include "dpaa_flavor.h"
+#include "dpaa_eth.h"
 
-struct dpaa_priv;
 struct qman_fq;
 struct qm_dqrr_entry;
 struct xsk_buff_pool;
@@ -66,10 +68,43 @@ static int af_xdp_pool_xsk_pool_detach(struct dpaa_priv *priv, u16 queue_id)
 return -EOPNOTSUPP;
 }
 
+/*
+ * af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup - kick the NAPI/QMan portal for an XSK queue
+ *
+ * Patch 0074 (Phase 1 hot-path wake gate, spec sec 5.2):
+ *   For XDP_WAKEUP_RX, resolve the NAPI associated with the qband and
+ *   schedule it via napi_schedule_irqoff() so the dpaa_eth_poll() loop
+ *   re-runs and drains any pending DQRR entries into the XSK fill ring.
+ *
+ *   The qmap[].napi slot is populated by the flavor module's future
+ *   xsk_pool_attach (patch 0075) once the dedicated XSK BMan channel
+ *   and its NAPI context have been brought up.  Until that lands, the
+ *   slot reads NULL and we return -ENOENT so the XSK core sees a clean
+ *   error (no NAPI bound on this qband) instead of NULL-deref'ing in
+ *   the IRQ-off scheduler path.  XDP_WAKEUP_TX handling lands with
+ *   patch 0078 (qman_p_irqsource_add poke of the egress portal).
+ */
 static int af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup(struct dpaa_priv *priv, u32 queue_id,
   u32 flags)
 {
-return -EOPNOTSUPP;
+struct napi_struct *napi;
+
+if (!priv)
+return -EINVAL;
+if (queue_id >= DPAA1_XSK_MAX_QBANDS)
+return -EINVAL;
+
+napi = READ_ONCE(priv->qmap[queue_id].napi);
+if (!napi)
+return -ENOENT;
+
+if (flags & XDP_WAKEUP_RX) {
+if (!napi_if_scheduled_mark_missed(napi))
+napi_schedule_irqoff(napi);
+}
+
+/* XDP_WAKEUP_TX path arrives with patch 0078. */
+return 0;
 }
 
 static void af_xdp_pool_xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup(struct dpaa_priv *priv,
